==1958 300D==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300D
| image = 1958 Chrysler 300D Hardtop.jpg
| caption =
| related = [[DeSoto Adventurer]]
| production = {{unbulleted list |1958 |809 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list |2-door [[hardtop]] |2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|392|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler Hemi engine#392|FirePower]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| wheelbase = {{convert|126.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="flory 50s" />
| length = {{convert|220|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
| width = {{convert|78.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
}}

The 1958 model year was to be the last use of the [[Chrysler FirePower engine|FirePower Hemi]] in the 300. The engine was still {{convert|392|CID|L|1|abbr=on}}, but tuned to {{convert|380|hp|kW|abbr=on}} as standard. Thirty-five cars were built with [[fuel injection]] and delivered {{convert|390|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, but the system was troublesome and most cars soon had it replaced with the standard twin-quad carburetor setup. A 300D was driven to {{convert|156.387|mph|km/h|3|abbr=on}} at the [[Bonneville Salt Flats]] that year. A total of 618 hardtops and 191 convertibles were produced, in part due to a [[Recession of 1958|recession]].
{{clear}}

==1959 300E==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300E
| image = Chrysler 300 1959.jpg
| caption =
| related = [[DeSoto Adventurer]]
| production = {{unbulleted list |1959 |647 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list |2-door [[hardtop]] |2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#413|Golden Lion]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| length = {{convert|220.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} <ref name="flory 50s" />
| wheelbase = {{convert|126|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} <ref name="flory 50s" />
}}

The 1959 model year saw the Hemi engines replaced by Chrysler's new [[Chrysler RB engine#413|Golden Lion]] wedge-head V8 at {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} displacement (which Chrysler called "lion-hearted").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Chrysler_and_Imperial/1959_Chrysler/1959_Chrysler_Brochure/1959%20Chrysler-01.html |title=1959 Chrysler Brochure |website=oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-13}}</ref> Power output remained about the same at {{convert|380|hp|kW|abbr=on}}. Total sales included 522 coupes and 125 convertibles. Power [[swivel seat]]s were standard.<ref name="flory 50s" />
{{clear}}

==1960 300F==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300F
| image = 1960 Chrysler 300F.JPG
| caption = 1960 Chrysler 300F Hardtop
| related = [[DeSoto Adventurer]]
| production = {{unbulleted list |1960 |1,217 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list |2-door [[hardtop]] |2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#413|RB]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| transmission = {{unbulleted list |3-speed automatic |4-speed Pont-à-Mousson [[Manual transmission|manual]] (racing/special order)}}
| wheelbase = {{convert|126|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Langworth |first=Richard |title=Encyclopedia of American Cars 1930–1980 |year=1984 |publisher=Publications International, Ltd. |isbn=0-88176-203-2}}</ref>
| length = {{convert|219.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="krause publications">{{cite book |title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946–1975 |publisher=Krause Publications |ISBN=0-87341-027-0 |editor=Gunnell, John A.}}</ref>
| width = {{convert|79.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="flory 60s" />
}}

The 1960 '''300F''' introduced a new [[Chrysler RB engine#413|{{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} Wedge]] engine delivering {{convert|375|hp|abbr=on}} in standard form. To boost power at lower and mid&nbsp;rpms, a special "cross-ram" intake manifold was derived. Instead of the normal [[V8 engine]] central intake manifold with [[carburetor]](s) on top, the cross-ram consisted of two pairs of {{convert|30|in|mm|abbr=on}} long tuned pipes that criss-crossed so that each set fed the opposite side of the engine. The carburetors and air cleaners hung off the sides of the engine over the fender wells. These long tubes were tuned so that resonances in the column of air helped force air into the cylinders at those engine speeds. Also new were four individual, leather bucket seats with a full length console from dash to rear seatback. Swivelling front seats were fitted as standard equipment.<ref>[http://www.300f.com/info.htm Chrysler 300F Information] Retrieved on 10 April 2012</ref>

A special {{convert|400|hp|abbr=on}} "short ram" version was produced for competition; in this, the tuned portion of the stacks was only {{convert|15|in|mm|abbr=on}} long (though the overall tube length remained at 30"), so that the resonant effect was produced at higher engine speeds. Only 15 "short ram" cars were produced; these were also fitted with the exotic but often troublesome French Pont-a-Mousson 4-speed manual transmissions developed for the Chrysler-powered [[Facel Vega]]. Approximately 4 of these "Special GTs" are known to exist, including one convertible and one with air conditioning; it is believed that 15 were originally produced.

The bodywork was also redone for 1960, using Chrysler's new lightweight [[unibody]] construction and given sharper-edged styling with outward-tilting fins that were visually separated from sides. The "toilet seat" trunk lid contributed to a demeaning opinion of the 300F and was done away with after this one year of production.

Sales increased to 969 coupes and 248 convertibles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.300f.com/info.htm|title=300F Information|publisher=Nick's Garage|accessdate=25 October 2010}}</ref>
{|
| [[File:Chrysler 300F.jpg|thumb|200px|Chrysler 300F Hardtop]]
| [[File:Chrysler 300F 1960.JPG|thumb|200px|The 300F featured swivelling front seats as standard equipment]]
| [[File:Chrysler 300F cross ram.jpg|thumb|200px|Chrysler 300F cross-ram]]
|}
{{clear}}

==1961 300G==

{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300G
| image = File:61 Chrysler 300 G (7324697482).jpg
| caption = 1961 Chrysler 300-G
| production = 1961
| body_style = {{unbulleted list|2-door [[coupe]]|2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#413|RB]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| transmission = {{unbulleted list |3-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] |3-speed ''TorqueFlite'' automatic |3-speed "Code 281" manual (race/special order)}}
| wheelbase = {{convert|126|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
| length = {{convert|219.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="krause publications" />
| width = {{convert|79.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="flory 60s" />
}}

The 1961 '''300G''' saw another restyle. The grille, formerly wider at the bottom than the top, was inverted; the quad headlights, formerly side-by-side, were arranged in angled fashion, inward at the bottom,<ref name="krause publications" /> in a manner reminiscent of 1958-1960 [[Lincoln Continental#Third generation (1958–1960)|Lincolns]], 1959 [[Buick Electra#1959–1960|Buicks]] and the 1963-1966 [[Rolls-Royce Silver Cloud#Silver Cloud III|Rolls-Royce Silver Cloud Mulliner Park Ward]] coupe. Small parking lamps below the headlights were likewise slanted and V-shaped, and the front bumper was canted up at each end, scoop-like. At the rear, the taillights were moved from the fins to the tail below them, and the fins were made sharper-pointed. Power windows were standard.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946-1975|publisher=krause publications|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor=Gunnell, John A.}}</ref>

Mechanically, the cross-ram "short ram" and "long ram" engines remained the same, although the expensive French [[manual transmission]] was dropped, and replaced by a more reliable and still expensive Chrysler racing manual transmission (referred to as 'option code 281'). There are currently only five cars with this transmission. Code 281 cars may have been built for the 1961 Daytona Flying Mile, although like the 1960 F Specials, no specific records were kept by Chrysler. Unlike the 300F Specials (which were randomly pulled from the line and upgraded for the Flying Mile), the 300Gs had a specific build code (281).
{{clear}}

==1962 300H==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300H
| image = Chrysler 300H Convertible 1962.jpg
| caption =
| production = {{unbulleted list |1962 |570 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list |2-door [[coupe]] |2-door [[convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#413|RB]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| transmission = 3-speed automatic
| wheelbase = {{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="flory 60s" />
| length = {{convert|214.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
| width = {{convert|79.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
}}

From 1962s '''300H''', the fins were gone, as was the letter series' unique place in the Chrysler lineup; there was now a whole Chrysler 300 Sport Series (which included a four-door hardtop along with a two-door hardtop and convertible), along with the 300H. Externally there was little difference between the 300H and the 300 Sport Series (except for a "300H" badge on the driver's side of the trunk), and many of the 300H's features could be ordered as options on the other models. Under the hood of the 300H the cross ram engine became an option, and there was a return to the inline dual 4-barrel carburetor setup of the 300E as the base powerplant. With a slight power boost and a {{convert|300|lb|kg|abbr=on}} lighter body, the 300H was faster than the 300G, but the loss of exclusivity coupled with high prices made this the slowest-selling letter series year yet, with only 435 coupes and 135 convertibles sold. The regular 300 (non-letter) series used a [[Chrysler B engine#383|{{convert|383|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} B engine]].

All 300s for 1962 were demoted to the Chrysler Newport/Dodge 880 122-inch wheelbase body.
{{clear}}

==1963 300J==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300J
| image = 1963 Chrysler 300 (35586932535).jpg
| caption =
| production = {{unbulleted list |1963 |400 produced}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#413|RB]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| body_style = 2-door [[coupe]]
| transmission = 3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]
| wheelbase={{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="flory 60s" />
| length = {{convert|215.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
| width = {{convert|79|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
}}

Further restyling for the 1963 '''300J''' (the letter "I" was skipped because people would confuse it for the numeral "1".) left the car with a smoother, more angular 1960s look. (Shared with the Newport and New Yorker series, this body design was the last one styled during Virgil Exner's term as Chrysler's styling chief.) The letter-series convertible was dropped, leaving the hardtop. The only engine available was the [[Chrysler RB engine#413|{{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ram-induction V8]], with an increase of {{convert|10|hp|abbr=on}} from 1962. A redesigned and more sumptuous interior featured an oddly squared steering wheel. The 300J was faster than the standard 300H of the year before, with a {{convert|142|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} top speed, 8.0 seconds 0-60&nbsp;mph, and a standing quarter mile time of 15.8 seconds with a terminal velocity of {{convert|89|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. Sales were especially poor, with only 400 cars produced. As for the non-letter 300, the 300 convertible was the official pace car for the 1963 Indianapolis 500-Mile Race. Power steering was standard.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Chrysler_and_Imperial/1963_Chrysler/1963_Chrysler_Brochure/1963%20Chrysler-07.html |title=1963 Chrysler Brochure |website=oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==1964 300K==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300K
| image = 64 Chrysler 300-K (9684653462).jpg
| production = {{unbulleted list |1964 |3,647 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list |2-door [[hardtop]] |2-door [[convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#413|RB]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| transmission = {{unbulleted list |3-speed automatic |4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]}}
| wheelbase = {{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
| length = {{convert|215.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="krause publications" />
| width = {{convert|80|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
}}

The convertible returned for the 1964 '''300K''', but the "cross-ram" engine became an extra-cost option available on the 300K only. A [[Chrysler RB engine#413|{{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} Wedge]] with a single Carter AFB 3614S 4-barrel carburetor, a regular intake manifold, and {{convert|360|hp|kW|abbr=on}} was the new standard engine. Leather upholstery was no longer standard either. All this reduced the baseline price by over a thousand dollars, and sales responded with the largest total ever; 3,022 coupes and 625 convertibles. A center console was standard.<ref name="ReferenceA" />
{{clear}}

==1965 300L==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Chrysler 300L
| image = 1966 Chrysler 300L convertible.jpg
| caption = 1965 Chrysler 300L Convertible
| production = {{unbulleted list|1965|2,845 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list|2-door [[hardtop]]|2-door [[convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler RB engine#413|RB]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]]
| transmission = {{unbulleted list |3-speed ''[[TorqueFlite]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] |4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]}}
| wheelbase = {{convert|124|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="flory 60s">{{cite book |last=Flory |first=J. "Kelly" Jr. |title=American Cars, 1960 to 1972; Every Model, Year by Year |year=2004 |publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers |ISBN=978-0-7864-1273-0}}</ref>
| length = {{convert|218.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
| width = {{convert|79.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}
}}

The 1965 '''300L''' was the eleventh and final model in the traditional letter series. Like every other 1965 Chrysler, it featured a completely restyled body with the crisp lines, slab sides and a tall greenhouse that were introduced by [[Elwood Engel]], successor of Virgil Exner as Chrysler's head of styling. It was a linear look and the panoramic windshield that had been used since 1957 was abandoned. The car had grown two inches in wheelbase and three inches in overall length. Both 2-door [[hardtop]] (with crease lines in the roof sheetmetal for the then-popular "convertible look") and 2-door [[convertible]] body styles were available. The cross-ram 390&nbsp;hp engine had been discontinued, leaving the [[Chrysler RB engine#413|{{convert|413|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} engine]] with regular inlet manifold, single 4-barrel carburetion, unsilenced air cleaner, special camshaft and dual exhaust as the only engine option. Engine output was {{convert|360|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, as in the previous year. The buyer could choose between the standard 3-speed [[TorqueFlite]] automatic and the no-cost option 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] with Hurst shift linkage. Every feature on the 300L could be ordered as an option on the regular 300; thus, the only difference was the 300L-exclusive ornamentation. This consisted of round "300L" medallions at the center of the die-cast grille star and in the middle of the textured aluminum applique between the taillights, a red-paint-filled full-length beltline molding, and a rectangular die-cast "300" badge on rear fenders.
Tested by car magazine [[Motor Trend]], a TorqueFlite-equipped 300L 2-door Hardtop accelerated from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} in 8.8 seconds, and covered the quarter mile in 17.3 seconds with a terminal speed of {{convert|82|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name="MT 300L">{{cite magazine |first=John |last=Elthridge |title=Chrysler 300-L Road Test |magazine=[[Motor Trend]] |issue=March 1965 |pages=36–41}}</ref> A total of 2,405 300L hardtops and 440 convertibles were produced.<ref name="flory 60s" />

