</gallery>
{{clear}}

==1970 Hurst 300==
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Hurst 300
| image = Chrysler 300 Hurst.JPG
| caption =
| production = {{unbulleted list|1970|501 produced}}
| body_style = {{unbulleted list|2-door [[coupe]]|2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]}}
| engine = {{convert|440|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Chrysler B engine#440|TNT]]'' V8
| transmission = 3-speed ''[[TorqueFlite#A727 (36RH/37RH)|Torqueflite A727]]'' automatic
}}
{{see also|Chrysler 300 non-letter series#1969–1971}}
The 1970 ''Hurst 300'' lacks the single-letter suffix of its forebears and appeared five years after the last Letter Series Chrysler, the 300L. Many automobile historians do not include the Hurst 300 as a Letter Series model. The concept of the car, however, does fit with the Letter Series cars, as it was a high-performance variant of the luxury 300, built with the input of aftermarket parts manufacturer [[Hurst Performance]]. Only 501 units are believed to have been built.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}

The Hurst 300s were all 2-door and shared a white and gold paint scheme similar to the [[Oldsmobile]] and [[Pontiac]] Hurst models of the day. The scooped hood and trunk lid (with a molded spoiler) are both fiberglass. All Hurst 300s had satin tan leather interiors that were straight out of the [[Imperial (automobile)#Fourth generation (1969–1973)|Imperial]] and could be had with column- or console-mounted 727 automatics. All came with the {{convert|375|hp|abbr=on}}  {{convert|440|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} 4-barrel ''TNT'' V8 engine.

Of the 501 units sold, one convertible is documented having been used as a Hurst promotional car and another is believed to have been dealer equipped with a {{convert|426|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} Hemi, also, a convertible.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
{{clear}}

== Collectibility ==
All original letter series cars are considered collectible {{As of|2005|lc=on}}, but the early years are much more desirable. The C-300 and 300B, especially red/maroon examples{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}, are increasingly becoming some of the most valuable models of all 1950s performance cars due to their exquisite styling, high performance, and rarity.  The 300C through 300G convertibles are the most desirable price-wise due to their scarcity and low survival rates; the coming of the [[Chrysler 300 non-letter series|regular 300 series cars]] in 1962 makes the subsequent letter series seem less special and less desirable to collectors.

At an auction at the Robson Estate in [[Gainesville, Georgia]] on November 13, 2010, the sole 1960 300F convertible equipped with the factory {{convert|400|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} engine and the Pont-a-Mousson 4-speed sold for $437,250.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rmauctions.com/auction-results-overview.cfm?SaleCode=MR10|title=CLASSIC CAR FEVER SWEEPS GAINESVILLE, GEORGIA, November 13, 2010|publisher=[[RM Auctions]]|accessdate=25 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120125529/http://www.rmauctions.com/auction-results-overview.cfm?SaleCode=MR10|archive-date=2011-01-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>

There was one concept vehicle called the Chrysler 300, created in 1991. It featured a sports car body and a [[Dodge Viper|Viper]] engine. It was never produced.

The 300 letter series name was resurrected in 1999 on the [[Chrysler 300M]]; but it is the 2005 [[Chrysler 300|300C]] that is closest to the original with its rear-wheel drive, and V8 engine once again bearing the "[[Chrysler Hemi engine|Hemi]]" name.

