The '''Chrysler Turbine Car''' is an [[automobile]] powered by a [[gas turbine|turbine engine]] which was produced by [[Chrysler Corporation|Chrysler]] from 1963 to 1964. Its [[List of auto parts#Body and main part|body]] was made by the Italian design studio [[Carrozzeria Ghia|Ghia]], and Chrysler completed its assembly in [[Detroit]]. The [[Chrysler turbine engines|Chrysler turbine engine program]] that produced the Turbine Car began during the late 1930s, and created multiple prototypes that successfully completed numerous long-distance trips in the 1950s and early 1960s.

The A-831 engines that powered the Ghia-designed Turbine Car could operate on many different fuels, required less maintenance, and lasted longer than conventional piston engines, although they were much more expensive to produce. A total of 55 cars were built: five [[prototype]]s and a limited run of 50 cars for a public user program. The car's design was created by [[Elwood Engel]] and the Chrysler studios. A two-door [[hardtop]] [[coupé|coupe]], it featured [[power brakes]], [[power steering]], and a [[TorqueFlite]] transmission, and was coated with a metallic, [[root beer]]-colored paint known as "turbine bronze".

After testing, Chrysler conducted a user program from October 1963 to January 1966 that involved 203 individual drivers in 133 different cities across the United States cumulatively driving more than one million miles (1.6 million km). The program helped the company determine a variety of problems with the cars, notably with their complicated starting procedure, relatively unimpressive [[acceleration]], and sub-par [[Fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] and noise level. The experience also revealed key advantages of the turbine engines, including their remarkable durability, smooth operation, and relatively modest maintenance requirements.

After the conclusion of the user program in 1966, Chrysler reclaimed all of the cars and destroyed all but nine of them; Chrysler kept two cars, five are displayed at museums in the United States, and two are in private collections. Chrysler's turbine engine program ultimately ended in 1979, largely due to the failure of the engines to meet government [[emission standard|emissions regulations]], relatively poor fuel economy, and as a prerequisite of receiving a government loan in 1979.

==Background==
Chrysler began researching [[gas turbine|turbine engines]] for aviation applications during the late 1930s, led primarily by executive engineer [[George Huebner]]. After World War II, Huebner was part of a group of engineers who began exploring the idea of powering a car with a turbine.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=2–3}} Other members of the secretive Chrysler research team which worked on automotive turbines included fellow engineers [[Bud Mann]] and [[Sam B. Williams]].{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=4–7}} The concept intrigued them, largely because turbine engines have fewer moving parts than their [[reciprocating engine|piston-powered counterparts]] and can run on a variety of fuels.<ref name="Lehto Road & Track">{{Cite news |url = http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/a33239/that-time-the-president-of-mexico-rode-in-a-turbine-chrysler-fueled-by-tequila/ |title = That Time the President of Mexico Rode in a Turbine Chrysler Fueled by Tequila |last = Lehto |first = Steve |date = April 17, 2017 |work = [[Road & Track]] |access-date = June 21, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170622181133/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/a33239/that-time-the-president-of-mexico-rode-in-a-turbine-chrysler-fueled-by-tequila/ |archive-date = June 22, 2017 |url-status = live |df = mdy-all }}</ref> According to historian Charles K. Hyde, by the mid-1950s Chrysler "led the way in terms of gas turbine research"{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=203}} (although [[General Motors]] and [[Rover Company|Rover]] also built operational turbine cars after World War II).<ref name="Truett">{{Cite news |url = http://www.autonews.com/article/20160517/BLOG06/160519904/chrysler-turbine-car-shows-the-future-is-always-changing |title = Chrysler Turbine car shows the future is always changing |last = Truett |first = Richard |date = May 17, 2016 |work = [[Automotive News]] |access-date = June 21, 2017 }}</ref>

After improving their turbine design, most notably by engineering a [[regenerative heat exchanger|regenerator]] to resolve an issue with [[heat exchanger|heat exchange]], the Chrysler team's efforts reached early maturity when they mated a turbine to an otherwise-stock 1954 [[Plymouth Belvedere]].{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=8–9}} Heating and cooling and emissions and exhaust were among the principal engineering challenges which faced the turbine engine.<ref name="Truett"/> Chrysler tested the Belvedere, claiming that its turbine engine contained 20 percent fewer parts and weighed {{convert|200|lbs|kg}} less than comparable, conventional piston engines.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=10}} On June 16, 1954, the company publicly unveiled the turbine-powered Belvedere at its [[Chelsea Proving Grounds]] in [[Chelsea, Michigan]], in front of over 500 reporters.{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=203}}{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=12}}{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=275}}

Chrysler unveiled its next turbine car, a 1956 Plymouth, on March 23, 1956; Huebner drove it {{convert|3,020|mi|km}} on a four-day trip from [[New York City]] to [[Los Angeles]].{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=203}}{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=15–17}} Although the car was shadowed by a 14-person convoy of mechanics with fuel and spare parts,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418272/leo_donovan_turbine_car_heads_west/|title=Turbine Car Heads West|last=Donovan|first=Leo|date=March 27, 1956|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|access-date=August 29, 2017|via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830105359/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418272/leo_donovan_turbine_car_heads_west/|archivedate=August 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> it only required two minor repairs on the trip (neither of which were engine-related).{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=275}} The coast-to-coast journey's success led Chrysler to double the size of its turbine program and move it from [[Highland Park, Michigan]], to a larger facility on Greenfield Road in [[Detroit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418316/leo_donovan_turbine_test_stepped_up/|title=Turbine Test Stepped Up|last=Donovan|first=Leo|date=February 13, 1957|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=August 29, 2017|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830104100/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418316/leo_donovan_turbine_test_stepped_up/|archivedate=August 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=18}}

The program began generating a number of [[patent]] applications in 1957, due largely to the contributions of metallurgist [[Amedee Roy]] and engineer [[Giovanni Savonuzzi]].{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=18–19}} The next iteration of the Chrysler turbine engine (the second-generation engine) was placed into a 1959 Plymouth, which averaged {{convert|19.4|mpgus}} on a trip from Detroit to [[Woodbridge, New Jersey]].{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=20}}{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=278}} This mileage was substantially higher than the {{convert|13|mpgus||abbr=on}} achieved with the first-generation turbine on the 1956 New York-to-Los Angeles journey.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=275}}{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=204}}

After Chrysler named former accountant [[Lynn Townsend]] its new president in 1961,{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=21–22}} the company unveiled its next, third-generation turbine engine on February 28;{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=22–23}} the CR2A was the first Chrysler turbine engine to be officially named.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=278}} Unlike its more-experimental predecessors, the CR2A was designed with an eye on costs and production methods.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=280}} While the engine was under development in May 1960, Huebner said that it would serve as its own [[torque converter]], generate {{Convert|140|hp|}}, have an acceleration lag of 1.5 seconds (compared with nine seconds for its predecessor), and weigh {{Convert|450|lbs|kg|abbr=on}}—{{Convert|150|lbs|kg|abbr=on}} less than a comparably sized piston engine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418674/fred_olmsted_world_of_wheels_third/ |title=Third Chrysler Turbine Due for Auto Test Soon |last=Olmsted |first=Fred |date=May 11, 1960 |work=Detroit Free Press |access-date=August 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830145831/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418674/fred_olmsted_world_of_wheels_third/ |archive-date=August 30, 2017 |url-status=live |via=Newspapers.com {{open access}} |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

Third-generation turbines were mated to a variety of vehicles, including a 2.5-ton 1960 Dodge truck and the [[Chrysler Turboflite]] concept car.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=22–23}}{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=281}} Refined CR2A turbines were installed into a 1962 [[Dodge Dart]] and [[Plymouth Fury]]; the Dart was driven from New York City to Los Angeles in December 1961, and the Fury completed a journey from Los Angeles to [[San Francisco]] in January 1962.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=23–25}}{{sfn|Norbye|1975|pp=282–283}} After Huebner arrived in Los Angeles with the Dart, he spent two hours giving journalists rides in the turbine-powered car.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=23–25}}

Chrysler had [[Barnstorming|barnstormed]] its fleet of turbine cars to dealers across North America, Europe and Mexico by February 1962, visiting 90 cities, giving rides to almost 14,000 people, and being seen by millions more.<ref name="Olmsted Public Sees Turbine Cars">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418645/fred_olmsted_world_of_wheels_public/|title=Public Sees Turbine Cars|last=Olmsted|first=Fred|date=February 2, 1962|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=August 29, 2017|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830105253/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418645/fred_olmsted_world_of_wheels_public/|archivedate=August 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=27–29}} The third-generation turbine program ended at the 1962 [[Chicago Auto Show]] that month, where the company displayed its turbine-powered fleet. Shortly before the show Chrysler announced an upcoming fourth-generation turbine engine it planned to install in a limited run of 50–75 cars which would be loaned to the public at no cost in late 1963,{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=283}}<ref name="Turbine Cars Due in 1963">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418370/turbine_cars_due_in_1963/ |title=Turbine Cars Due in 1963 |date=December 28, 1961 |work=Detroit Free Press |access-date=August 29, 2017 |via=Newspapers.com {{open access}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830103811/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418370/turbine_cars_due_in_1963/ |archivedate=August 30, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=30}} a decision largely due to enthusiastic public response to the barnstorming tour.{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=204}}

==Engine==
{{See also|Chrysler turbine engines}}
[[File:Exploded view of the A831 gas turbine.jpg|thumb|alt=See caption|Exploded view of the A-831 turbine engine at the Walter P. Chrysler Museum]]

The Chrysler Turbine Car is powered by the A-831, Chrysler's fourth-generation turbine engine. The most notable difference from its predecessor, the CR2A, was its use of twin regenerators (one mounted on either side of the [[gasifier]]) instead of a single top cover-mounted heat exchanger.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=283}} This design helped the A-831 trim {{convert|40|lbs|kg}} from the CR2A's weight,{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=284}} reducing it to a relatively-light {{convert|410|lbs|0|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=31}} Huebner described the turbine as similar to a [[jet engine]], noting that it had only one [[spark plug]] and about 80 percent fewer parts than a typical automotive piston engine.<ref name="TucsonPreview"/> Due to their construction, the engines did not require [[antifreeze]], a cooling system, a [[radiator (engine cooling)|radiator]], [[connecting rod]]s, or [[crankshaft]]s.<ref name="Turbine Cars Due in 1963"/><ref name="Friedlander">{{Cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1973/04/29/archives/gas-turbines-present-and-future-father-of-the-turbine-sluggish-and.html |title = Gas Turbines: Present and Future |last = Friedlander |first = Paul J. C. |date = April 29, 1973 |work = [[The New York Times]] |access-date = August 29, 2017 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170830105037/http://www.nytimes.com/1973/04/29/archives/gas-turbines-present-and-future-father-of-the-turbine-sluggish-and.html |archivedate = August 30, 2017 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>

The A-831 could operate on [[diesel fuel]], [[gasoline|unleaded gasoline]], [[kerosene]], and [[JP-4 (fuel)|JP-4 jet fuel]];{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=36}} [[leaded gasoline]] damaged it.<ref name="Turner">{{Cite news |url = http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/11/08/jay.leno.cars/index.html |title = Jay Leno shows off car that 'runs on tequila and perfume' |last = Turner |first = Lianne |date = November 16, 2010 |publisher = [[CNN]] |access-date = June 21, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170802164137/http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/11/08/jay.leno.cars/index.html |archive-date = August 2, 2017 |url-status = live |df = mdy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=46}} According to Chrysler, it could burn a variety of unusual fuels ranging from [[furnace oil]] and [[perfume]] to [[peanut oil|peanut]] and [[soybean oil]]s.<ref name="Lehto Road & Track"/><ref name="Turbine Cars Due in 1963"/><ref name="Friedlander"/> Mexican president [[Adolfo López Mateos]] ran one of the cars on [[tequila]] after Chrysler engineers confirmed that it would do so.<ref name="Lehto Road & Track"/>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=84}}

The engine produced {{convert|130|bhp||abbr=on}} at 36,000 [[revolutions per minute]] (rpm), {{convert|425|lbft||abbr=on}} of [[torque]], and [[idle (engine)|idled]] between 18,000 and 22,000 rpm.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=31}}<ref name="TucsonPreview"/>{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=289}} At idle, its exhaust did not exceed {{convert|180|°F|°C}}.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=290}} When driven at {{Convert|120|mph|0|abbr=on}}, the turbine ran at its maximum of 60,000 rpm.<ref name="TucsonPreview">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12568132/tucson_daily_citizen/|title=Tucson gets a Preview of Chrysler's Turbine Car|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=March 18, 1965|work=[[Tucson Daily Citizen]]|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802171932/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12568132/tucson_daily_citizen/|archive-date=August 2, 2017|url-status=live|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The A-831's [[compressor]] had a [[overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]] of 4:1 and an efficiency of 80 percent;{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=284}} its [[combustor]] operated at 95 percent efficiency.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=286}}

Compared to conventional piston engines, turbine engines generally require less maintenance, last longer, and start more easily in cold conditions;{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=203}} the A-831 started properly at temperatures as low as {{convert|-20|°F|°C}}.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=292}} The first car to receive an A-831 was a Plymouth Fury.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=31}} In this [[Carrozzeria Ghia|Ghia]]-built turbine car, the engine had a [[0 to 60 mph|0-to-{{Convert|60|mph|kph|abbr=on}} time]] of about 12 seconds.<ref name="Florea">{{Cite news |url = https://www.autoevolution.com/news/1963-chrysler-turbine-car-sounds-like-a-jet-plane-video-77142.html |title = 1963 Chrysler Turbine Car Sounds Like a Jet Plane |last = Florea |first = Ciprian |date = February 18, 2014 |work = [[autoevolution]] |access-date = June 21, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170802165410/https://www.autoevolution.com/news/1963-chrysler-turbine-car-sounds-like-a-jet-plane-video-77142.html |archive-date = August 2, 2017 |url-status = live |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Due to the exotic materials and strict tolerances needed to build the engines and the [[investment casting]] method with which they were made, the A-831s were very expensive to produce;{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=32}} Chrysler never disclosed their actual cost.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=45}}

==Design==
The Turbine Car was designed in the Chrysler studios under the direction of [[Elwood Engel]], who had worked for the [[Ford Motor Company]] before moving to Chrysler.{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=204}}{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=22, 40}} Due to its resemblance to the Engel-designed [[Ford Thunderbird]], the car is occasionally called the "Englebird".{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=204}}{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=293}}{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=22, 40–41}} According to Huebner, the design was intended to compete with the [[Chevrolet Corvette]] in addition to the Thunderbird.<ref name="Olmsted Public Sees Turbine Cars"/>

The car's bodies were handmade by Italian design studio [[Carrozzeria Ghia|Ghia]], which had built a number of [[concept car]]s for Chrysler (including an [[Chrysler Imperial|Imperial]] limousine and the [[Chrysler Norseman|Norseman]]).{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=41}}<ref name="Hayes"/> The mostly completed Turbine Car bodies, which were assembled, painted, trimmed, and upholstered by Ghia in Italy, were shipped to Chrysler's Greenfield Road turbine facility in Detroit for final assembly; this consisted of installing the turbine engines, [[TorqueFlite]] transmissions, electrical wiring, and components such as [[vehicle audio|radios]] and heaters.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=42, 111}} Building an individual car may have cost as much as between $50,000 to $55,000 ({{Inflation|US|50,000|1964|fmt=eq|r=-3}} to {{Inflation|US|55,000|1964|fmt=eq|r=-3}});{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=44–45, 124}} Virgil Exner, Jr., estimates that the bodies themselves cost about $20,000 ({{Inflation|US|20,000|1964|fmt=eq|r=-3}}), although Chrysler never revealed the cost of each turbine engine.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=44–45}}{{Inflation-fn|US}}

The first five cars were completed in early 1962 as [[prototype]]s used for troubleshooting; each was slightly different from the others, varying in exterior color, interior upholstery, and roof material.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=42}} Early problems discovered from the prototypes included sluggish acceleration (attributed in part to the relatively heavy hand-built bodies) and vibration, ultimately determined to be caused by the tire treads and noticeable due to the unusual smoothness of the turbine engine.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=43–44}}

A total of 50 identical Turbine Cars were built between October 1963 and October 1964.<ref name="Adler">{{cite book |last = Adler |first = Dennis |last2 = Shelby |first2 = Carroll |title = 50 Cars to Drive |publisher = [[Globe Pequot Press]] |year = 2008 |page = 74 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Jc3ECwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 |isbn = 978-1-59921-230-2 |via = [[Google Books]] |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180206115852/https://books.google.com/books?id=Jc3ECwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 |archivedate = February 6, 2018 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=43}} They were all two-door [[hardtop]] [[coupé|coupes]], with air-over-oil [[power brakes]] and [[power steering]].<ref name="Piston Auto Engines Are Challenged">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13480017/piston_auto_engines_are_challenged/|title=Piston Auto Engines Are Challenged: Chrysler Unveils Turbine Power Plant|date=May 16, 1963|work=[[The News-Palladium]]|access-date=August 31, 2017|location=Benton Harbor, Michigan|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901153410/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13480017/piston_auto_engines_are_challenged/|archivedate=September 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=46–48}} The cars had [[independent front suspension]] with a [[coil spring]] at each front wheel, eschewing Chrysler's contemporary-standard independent front longitudinal [[torsion bar suspension|torsion bar]] system (although their rear suspension utilized off-the-shelf [[leaf spring]]s). All four wheels were equipped with power-assisted [[drum brake]]s.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=293}}

[[File:1963 Chrysler Turbine Coupe (31527648910).jpg|thumb|left|upright 1.0|alt=Red front exterior, seen through the driver's side window|The Turbine Car interior]]

The car body is finished in a metallic, [[root beer]]-colored paint known as "turbine bronze".{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=45}}<ref name="Piston Auto Engines Are Challenged"/> Its headlights, deeply-recessed taillights, turn signals, and pod-shaped backup lights are mounted in chrome [[bezel (jewellery)|bezels]]. The turbine-inspired style carries through to the [[center console (automobile)|center console]] design of the interior,<ref name="Hayes">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13480171/paul_r_hayes_auto_facts_200/|title=Auto Facts: 200 Motorists to Give Chrysler Turbine 'Ride-and-Drive' Test for Year|last=Hayes|first=Paul R.|date=May 20, 1963|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=August 31, 2017|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901112219/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13480171/paul_r_hayes_auto_facts_200/|archivedate=September 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> which has bronze-colored [[leather]] upholstery, deep-pile bronze carpet, and [[brushed aluminum]] accents.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=46}} The cars have black [[polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] hardtop roofs, leather-upholstered bucket seats, and [[whitewall tire]]s.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=123}}{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=124}}

The Turbine Car's [[dashboard]] is dominated by three large gauges: a [[speedometer]], a [[tachometer]], and [[pyrometer]], the latter monitoring the temperature of the turbine inlet (the engine's hottest component).{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=46}} Its appearance is mostly stock, although the tachometer and pyrometer display abnormally high readings compared to piston-engine cars: 46,000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|1,700|°F|°C}}, respectively.<ref name="Hayes"/> All 55 turbine cars had identical [[key (lock)|ignition keys]].{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=47}}
{{clear left}}

==User program==
[[File:Chrysler Turbine Car Worlds Fair 1964.jpg|thumb|alt=Car with its hood up in front of a World's Fair pavilion|Chrysler Turbine Car at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]]]]

Two of the cars gave rides to visitors at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]], and another went on a worldwide tour; 50 were lent to the general public as part of a user program.<ref name="Lehto Road & Track"/> The cars were given to drivers for a three-month period at no charge, aside from fuel costs; participants also gave Chrysler in-depth interviews within two weeks of returning their cars.{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=283}}{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=205}} During the user program, which ran from October 1963 to January 1966,<ref name="Lassa"/>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=112}} the cars' operational [[downtime]] was reduced from four percent early on to one percent by its conclusion.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=115}}

The user program helped identify a variety of problems with the cars, including [[starter (engine)|starter]] malfunction at high altitudes,{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=113}} difficulty in mastering the unusual eight-step starting procedure (which, for some users, resulted in engine damage),{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=57}} and the cars' relatively unimpressive acceleration.<ref name="Friedlander"/>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=88, 92, 117}} Nonetheless, the turbine engines were remarkably durable in comparison to contemporary piston engines.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=70}} The most-cited advantages of the turbine engine, according to the participants' interviews, were its smooth and vibration-free operation, reduced maintenance requirements, and ease of starting in different conditions; the most-common complaints concerned its slow acceleration, sub-par fuel economy, and relatively high noise level.{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=205}}<ref name="Simpson 2-Year Test Ended">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418760/roger_a_simpson_2year_test_ended/ |title=2-Year Test Ended: Gas Turbine Car is Great, But... |last=Simpson |first=Roger A. |date=April 13, 1966 |work=Detroit Free Press |access-date=August 29, 2017 |via=Newspapers.com {{open access}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830105510/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418760/roger_a_simpson_2year_test_ended/ |archivedate=August 30, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Investigating the latter complaint, Chrysler found that the distinctive sound of the car's turbine (reminiscent of a jet engine){{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=43}} was positively received by about 60 percent of those involved in the user program and disliked by about 20 percent of their fellow users.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=118}}

The cars had conspicuous warning labels cautioning drivers to avoid using leaded gasoline; although the turbine engine could run on it, the lead additive left debilitating deposits in it.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=46, 90–91}} The only fuel which Chrysler recommended not be used, it was by far the easiest to obtain during the user program.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=46}} Fuels commonly used by those participating in the user program included diesel and home [[heating oil]].<ref name="Lehto Road & Track"/>

More than 1 million miles (1.6 million km) were accumulated in testing by the 50 cars given to the public, which were driven by 203 users before the program ended in January 1966.{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=205}}<ref name="Simpson 2-Year Test Ended"/>{{sfn|Norbye|1975|pp=293–294}}{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=77, 116}} The users lived in 133 cities in the 48 [[contiguous United States|contiguous states]] and [[Washington, D.C.]]; 180 were male and 23 were female, their ages ranged from 21 to 70, and 60 percent were Chrysler owners.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=77}}{{sfn|Norbye|1975|p=294}}

==Legacy==
[[File:1963 Chrysler Turbine in Hershey PA.JPG|thumb|alt=Red Chrysler Turbine Car in a parking lot|Chrysler Turbine Car at the 1999 Antique Automobile Club of America show in Hershey, Pennsylvania]]
[[File:Chrysler Turbine (9394967311).jpg|thumb|alt=Another red car|Chrysler Turbine Car at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in Los Angeles]]
[[File:1963 Chrysler turbine car in film.png|thumb|alt=White Chrysler Turbine Car with a number on its side|Still of a turbine car in the 1964 film ''[[The Lively Set]]'']]

In April 1966, product planning and development vice president Harry E. Chesebrough noted that the 50 test cars would be taken off the road regardless of whether the Chrysler Turbine Car went into production.<ref name="Simpson 2-Year Test Ended"/> Chrysler destroyed 46 of the cars after it finished the user program and other public displays. Forty-five of the cars were burned and crushed at a [[Wrecking yard|scrapyard]] south of Detroit, and the other was destroyed at Chrysler's Chelsea Proving Grounds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418404/fred_olmsted_world_of_wheels/|title=Chrysler Corp. will chop|last=Olmsted|first=Fred|date=April 15, 1966|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=August 29, 2017|via=Newspapers.com {{open access}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830103923/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13418404/fred_olmsted_world_of_wheels/|archivedate=August 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=122}} A widely circulated explanation was that the cars were destroyed to avoid a substantial tariff on the imported Ghia bodies, although author Steve Lehto claims that this has been "largely discredited."{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=121}} The destruction of the cars was in line with the automobile industry's practice of not selling non-production or prototype cars to the public. According to Lehto, the decision was influenced by Chrysler's [[public relations]] concerns: the potential difficulty of keeping the cars running and fears that owners would replace the turbine powerplants with piston engines.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=121}} A Chrysler executive was quoted in ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'': "Our main objective is research, and we did not want turbines turning up on used-car lots."{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=121}} A similar practice was later used by General Motors with its [[General Motors EV1|EV1]] when it terminated the program and destroyed most of the cars in 2003.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=169}}

Chrysler's development of turbine engines continued from the late 1960s into the 1970s, resulting in the creation of fifth- and sixth-generation engines. The turbines ultimately failed to meet government [[emission standard|emissions regulations]] and had relatively poor [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]], despite promising early results and a $6.4 million contract from the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref name="Friedlander"/>{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=206}}<ref name="Norbye and Dunne September 1973">{{Cite magazine |last = Norbye |first = Jan P. |last2 = Dunne |first2 = Jim |date = September 1973 |title = For the Gas Turbine Car, It's Now or Never |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=scA6lVmzQA8C&pg=PA56 |journal = [[Popular Science]] |pages = 56–59 |via = Google Books |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180206115852/https://books.google.com/books?id=scA6lVmzQA8C&pg=PA56 |archivedate = February 6, 2018 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> According to Charles K. Hyde, the company's effort to enlarge and diversify its turbine program was unsuccessful and spread its "already-thin executive talent pool even thinner".{{sfn|Hyde|2003|p=206}} An October 1967 [[United States Department of Commerce|Department of Commerce]] report concluded that the turbine engine was "unsuited to automobiles".<ref name="Francis September 1968">{{Cite magazine |last = Francis |first = Devon |date = September 1968 |title = Is There a Steam Car in Your Future? |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hiUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64 |journal = Popular Science |pages = 64–67, 210–211 |via = Google Books |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180206115852/https://books.google.com/books?id=hiUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64 |archivedate = February 6, 2018 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Development continued on automotive turbines, in part because turbine exhaust contains fewer unburned [[hydrocarbon]]s and lower concentrations of other pollutants. In March 1971, the [[Williams Research Corporation]] continued developing a turbine engine with funding from the National Air Pollution Control Administration.<ref name="Norbye March 1971">{{Cite magazine |last = Norbye |first = Jan P. |date = March 1971 |title = Tiny 80-hp Gas Turbine to Power Compact Car |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ogAAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34 |journal = Popular Science |pages = 34 |via = Google Books |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180206115852/https://books.google.com/books?id=ogAAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34 |archivedate = February 6, 2018 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Chrysler's turbine engine development continued through the mid-1970s, with later compact versions of the engines being installed in the [[Dodge Aspen]].<ref name=CCMS76>{{citation | title = Final Report: Automotive Propulsion Systems Pilot Study | publisher = U.S. Department of Energy | author = The Pilot Study Working Group | id = CCMS-76 | page = 21 | date = 1978 }}</ref> However, the program as well as the seventh-generation engine were discontinued in 1979 as a requirement of the ''Chrysler Corporation Loan Guarantee Act of 1979'',<ref name="MT002">{{cite journal|last=Thomas|first=Phillip|title=Futuristic engines promised low maintenance, excellent power, and increased reliability at the height of the American Jet Age|journal=Motor Trend|issn=0027-2094|url=http://www.motortrend.com/news/stop-presses-theres-7th-generation-chrysler-turbine-engine-ebay/}}</ref> as well as due to its inability to attain enough fuel economy.<ref name="Truett"/> One Chrysler Turbine Car appeared in the 1964 film ''[[The Lively Set]]'', painted white with blue [[racing stripe]]s; it was the only Turbine Car not painted bronze.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=93}}

Only nine Chrysler Turbine Cars have survived.<ref name="Florea"/>{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=170}} Two are kept by Chrysler, out of three initially retained by the company; five are on display at museums around the United States, and two were acquired by private collectors.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=170–171}} Chrysler has displayed one of its cars at the [[Walter P. Chrysler Museum]] in [[Auburn Hills, Michigan]]. The five cars on museum display were donated to the [[Detroit Historical Museum]], the [[The Henry Ford|Henry Ford Museum]] in [[Dearborn, Michigan]], the [[Museum of Transportation]] in [[Kirkwood, Missouri]], the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in Los Angeles, and the [[Smithsonian Institution]] in Washington, D.C.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=170–171}} In 2005, the Detroit Historical Museum lent its car, which had been in warehouse storage, to the [[Gilmore Car Museum]] in [[Hickory Corners, Michigan]].{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=171}} All the cars donated to museums had their fan assemblies removed to render their engines inoperable,{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=170}} although the car owned by the Museum of Transportation was restored and returned to operating condition in the 1980s, allowing it to appear at car shows.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=171}}

Two Chrysler Turbine Cars have been acquired by private collectors.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=170}} One is owned by Frank Kleptz of [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] which was originally donated to the former [[National Automobile Museum|Harrah Collection]] in [[Reno, Nevada]], before being purchased by [[Domino's Pizza]] founder [[Tom Monaghan]] and sold to Kleptz.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=172}} The second is owned by comedian and television host [[Jay Leno]] who purchased one of the three Turbine Cars originally retained by Chrysler in 2009.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|p=171}} Leno's car was featured in the [[BBC]] television show ''[[James May's Cars of the People]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/dzck5x/james-mays-cars-of-the-people--s2-e3-james-mays-cars-of-the-people/|title=James May's Cars of the People: Series 2 – Episode 3|last=Butcher|first=David|work=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=December 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216091238/http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/dzck5x/james-mays-cars-of-the-people--s2-e3-james-mays-cars-of-the-people/|archive-date=December 16, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Both privately owned Chrysler Turbine Cars are operational.{{sfn|Lehto|2010|pp=172, 174–175}}

